b"[![](../../cdshop/cdinfo.jpg)](../../cdshop/index.htm)  \n[Sacred Texts](../../index.htm)  [Hinduism](../index.htm)  [Index](index.htm)\n[Previous](sbe48452.htm)  [Next](sbe48454.htm)\n\n* * *\n\n6\\. On account of injunction for such a one.\n\nThat knowledge is subordinate to works follows therefrom also that works are\nenjoined on him only who possesses knowledge. For texts such as 'He who has\nlearnt the Veda from a family of teachers,' &c. ( _Kh_. Up. VIII, 15), enjoin\nworks on him only who has mastered the sacred texts so as fully to understand\ntheir meaning--for this is the sense of the term 'learning' (adhyayana). Hence\nthe knowledge of Brahman also is enjoined ith a view to works only: it has no\nindependent result of its own.\n\n* * *\n\n[Next: 7. On account of definite rule](sbe48454.htm)\n\n"